{"detail":{"ID":53,"post_author":"1","post_date":"2016-12-06 12:58:49","post_date_gmt":"2016-12-06 12:58:49","post_content":"Stretching from entry of the property at the top of the hill down to the very edge of the bush at bottom, the house is split into five discrete pavilions, with the first near the entry used as garage and battery storage for solar energy harvested nearby. The main body of the house descends southward stepping down in four different parts. The rotation of its footprints gives the interior a variety of experience as it cascades down the hill constantly re-focusing different views of the landscape and changing sunlight angles. This is the vacation home for an American doctor, his wife and daughter located atop a hill in the remote rainforest of the Osa Peninsula of Costa Rica. The site is located in the center of the peninsula with distant views of the Golfo Dulce to the East and the Pacific Ocean to the West. From a very young age, the doctor has been fascinated by wilderness, and ever since he was old enough to travel by himself, he spent much time in the wild, visiting the Amazon, Africa, Belize, and other distant forests. The house is for him the realization of a long held project of a life in the proximity of exuberant nature. Located on a 98 hectare lot of virgin forest, the house occupies a small hill that was formally cultivated as a mango farm, the only portion of land that had been \u201ccivilized\u201d in any way, thus offering a simple solution for choice of site without the need for clearing of trees.","post_title":"<p>Casa Osa, CR 2009-2013<\/p>","post_excerpt":"","post_status":"publish","comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","post_password":"","post_name":"casa-osa","to_ping":"","pinged":"","post_modified":"2017-05-12 15:41:11","post_modified_gmt":"2017-05-12 15:41:11","post_content_filtered":"","post_parent":0,"guid":"http:\/\/obra.neptuno.digital\/?post_type=projects&#038;p=53","menu_order":0,"post_type":"projects","post